{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "In another work, Dean et al. (2021) introduce PepVAE, a framework for peptide generation that integrates a VAE with models for predicting antimicrobial activity, aimed at designing novel antimicrobial peptides (AMPs) based on sequence data and experimental minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) values.",
    "By strategically sampling from specific areas of the latent space, the framework facilitates the controlled synthesis of new AMP sequences with a minimal set of input parameters.",
    "VAEs have also been instrumental in their uses in image reconstruction, as demonstrated by Xu et al. (2023), where VAEs have been shown to reconstruct complete images from partial images of numbers.",
    "Based on the principles employed by Dean et al. (2021), VAEs can be trained on paleontological data to produce diverse fossil images or structural variations.",
    "Controlled and constrained exploration of latent space would allow for augmentation of imbalanced fossil classes in the datasets, by generating plausible variations of existing specimens, thereby enriching the dataset for research and analysis without needing new labeled data."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "In another work, Dean et al. (2021) introduce PepVAE, a framework for peptide generation that integrates a VAE with models for predicting antimicrobial activity, aimed at designing novel antimicrobial peptides (AMPs) based on sequence data and experimental minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) values.",
